<subSubSection id="C32C649FD56AD00D5F9309BA93C5FC44" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8B893714D56AD00D5F9309BA96F9FD36" blockId="6.[151,440,654,680]" box="[151,440,654,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
<heading id="D0C18078D56AD00D5F9309BA96F9FD36" bold="true" box="[151,440,654,680]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5F9309BA96F9FD36" bold="true" box="[151,440,654,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5F9309BA9627FD36" box="[151,358,654,680]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5F9309BA9627FD36" bold="true" box="[151,358,654,680]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Sepedon spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B893714D56AD00D5F9309EC93C5FC44" blockId="6.[151,1438,728,1720]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5FC809EC960BFD6F" box="[204,330,728,753]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5FC809EC960BFD6F" box="[204,330,728,753]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S. spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is characterized by the presence of a few short hairs, a little finer and longer than those on the thoracic dorsum, on the posterior slope of the callus between the posterior thoracic spiracle and wing base on the katatergite (=metapleural callus of authors). Also, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA74AE5D56AD00D5C6F0811933CFCA1" author="Knutson" box="[875,1149,805,831]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="60" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" refString="Knutson, L. &amp; Orth, R. E. (2001) Sepedon mcphersoni, n. sp., key to North American Sepedon, groups in Sepedon s. s., and intra- and intergeneric comparison (Diptera: Sciomyzidae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 103, 620 - 635." type="journal article" year="2001">
Knutson &amp; Orth (
<number id="3DFE2533D56AD00D5B3308119335FCA1" box="[1079,1140,805,831]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
characterized this group by the presence of a presutural intra-alar seta (sometimes referred to only as &quot;presutural&quot;). We have examined several hundred specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5EFF08469538FC15" box="[507,633,882,907]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5EFF08469538FC15" box="[507,633,882,907]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S. spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Western Palearctic and 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5B05084693DAFC15" box="[1025,1179,882,907]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5B05084693DAFC15" box="[1025,1179,882,907]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S. americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from North 
<collectingCountry id="F3217784D56AD00D5A34084692D8FC12" box="[1328,1433,882,908]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">America</collectingCountry>
. In fact, a distinct presutural intra-alar seta is absent in most specimens. When present, it is at most only twice as long as, and slightly more erect than, the surrounding hairs on the thoracic dorsum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32C649FD56AD00D5FC208D296E2F926" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B893714D56AD00D5FC208D2955BFAA8" blockId="6.[151,1438,728,1720]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
In this group only one holarctically distributed species with the Palaearctic nominate subspecies and the Nearctic 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5E080F3995AEFBB9" authority="Steyskal, 1951" authorityName="Steyskal" authorityYear="1951" box="[268,751,1037,1063]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="spinipes" subSpecies="americana">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E080F39965AFBB8" box="[268,283,1037,1062]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E2A0F399568FBB8" box="[302,553,1037,1062]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">spinipes americana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA74AE5D56AD00D5D360F3995AEFBB9" author="Steyskal" box="[562,751,1037,1063]" pageId="6" pageNumber="60" refString="Steyskal, G. C. (1951) The genus Sepedon Latreille in the Americas (Diptera: Sciomyzidae. The Wasmann Journal of Biology 8, 271 - 297." type="journal article" year="1951">
Steyskal, 
<number id="3DFE2533D56AD00D5DB40F3995AEFBB9" box="[688,751,1037,1063]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has been recognized. Steyskal distinguished his new subspecies in his key to the American species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5DD70F009476FBD3" box="[723,823,1076,1101]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5DD70F009476FBD3" box="[723,823,1076,1101]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Sepedon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by presence of the orbital spot, the slightly pruinose and bare middle part of the face, the haired katatergite (more precisely a supraspiracular convexity of the metathorax), the distinctly outwardly bowed posterior crossvein, the mid femur with a strong mid-anterior bristle, and the thickened and concolorous tawny hind femur. These characters are also well distinct in the nominate form of 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5E760FFB96B3FB76" box="[370,498,1230,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E760FFB96C0FB76" box="[370,385,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E940FFB96B3FB76" box="[400,498,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurring in the Palaearctic region as confirmed by Steyskal (l.c.) in material from 
<collectingCountry id="F3217784D56AD00D5FDF0FC19672FA91" box="[219,307,1269,1295]" name="France" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">France</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3217784D56AD00D5E450FC196D8FA91" box="[321,409,1269,1295]" name="Greece" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Greece</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F3217784D56AD00D5ED20FC1956BFA91" box="[470,554,1269,1295]" name="Latvia" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Latvia</collectingCountry>
. The only distinguishing character stated by him was the difference in structures of the male terminalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B893714D56AD00D5FC10E7696E2F926" blockId="6.[151,1438,728,1720]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
The recently re-examined representatives of both “subspecies“ prove that actually there are no external non-genitalic distinguishable characters among both taxa but some major structures of the male terminalia, especially the conspicuously different shape of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="130D2B91D56AD00D5C610EA494ACFA34" box="[869,1005,1424,1450]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1208,1232]" captionTargetBox="[186,1404,454,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,395,1184]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 27. Species of Sepedon spinipes group, male terminalia. 20 – 23. S. americana. 24 – 27. S. spinipes. 20, 24. Lateral view. 21, 25. Hypandrium in lateral view. 22, 26. Aedeagus in lateral view. 23, 27. Epiphallus in caudal view. Scales: 0.5 mm (Figs 20, 24), 0.3 mm (Figs 21 – 23, 24 – 27)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191321/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
Figs 
<number id="3DFE2533D56AD00D5CA40EA494ACFA34" box="[928,1005,1424,1450]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="22.26">22, 26</number>
</figureCitation>
), are even more different than within members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5E5F0E839540FA4E" box="[347,513,1462,1488]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscipennis">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E5F0E83962BFA4E" box="[347,362,1463,1488]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E7E0E839540FA4E" box="[378,513,1463,1488]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">fuscipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<figureCitation id="130D2B91D56AD00D5D650E8295AFFA4E" box="[609,750,1462,1488]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 19" captionStartId="5.[151,270,1420,1444]" captionTargetBox="[185,1388,691,1404]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,682,1414]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 19. Nearctic species of Sepedon fuscipennis group, details of male terminalia. 8, 12, 16. S. floridensis. 9, 13, 17. S. fuscipennis. 10, 14, 18. S. gracilicornis. 11, 15, 19. S. tenuicornis. 8 – 11. Hypandrium in lateral view. 12 – 15. Aedeagus in lateral view. 16 – 19. Epiphallus in caudal view. Scale: 0.3 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191320/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
Figs 
<number id="3DFE2533D56AD00D5D9A0E8295AFFA4E" box="[670,750,1462,1488]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="13.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="12.0">12–15</number>
</figureCitation>
). The male terminalia structures of 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5B9A0E83927DFA4E" box="[1182,1340,1462,1488]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5B9A0E8393ECFA4E" box="[1182,1197,1463,1488]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5BB80E83927DFA4E" box="[1212,1340,1463,1488]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fit well with the original figure published by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA74AE5D56AD00D5D5F0EE9943FFA69" author="Steyskal" box="[603,894,1501,1527]" pageId="6" pageNumber="60" refString="Steyskal, G. C. (1951) The genus Sepedon Latreille in the Americas (Diptera: Sciomyzidae. The Wasmann Journal of Biology 8, 271 - 297." type="journal article" year="1951">
Steyskal (
<number id="3DFE2533D56AD00D5DD50EE99451FA69" box="[721,784,1501,1527]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="1951.0">1951</number>
, 
<figureCitation id="130D2B91D56AD00D5C1A0EE99434FA69" box="[798,885,1501,1527]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1208,1232]" captionTargetBox="[186,1404,454,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,395,1184]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 27. Species of Sepedon spinipes group, male terminalia. 20 – 23. S. americana. 24 – 27. S. spinipes. 20, 24. Lateral view. 21, 25. Hypandrium in lateral view. 22, 26. Aedeagus in lateral view. 23, 27. Epiphallus in caudal view. Scales: 0.5 mm (Figs 20, 24), 0.3 mm (Figs 21 – 23, 24 – 27)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191321/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFE2533D56AD00D5C520EE99434FA69" box="[854,885,1501,1527]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="23.0">23</number>
</figureCitation>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and are markedly different from any species collected in the Nearctic Region. Therefore the differences found between 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5B080D3093CAF983" box="[1036,1163,1540,1566]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5B080D30935AF983" box="[1036,1051,1540,1565]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5B2F0D3093CAF983" box="[1067,1163,1540,1565]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5BC10D309223F983" box="[1221,1378,1540,1566]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5BC10D309395F983" box="[1221,1236,1540,1565]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5BE00D309223F983" box="[1252,1378,1540,1565]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be considered to be of a specific level in full accordance with the current general concept of species in the large genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5E210D65963BF9F4" box="[293,378,1617,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Sepedo" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E210D65963BF9F4" box="[293,378,1617,1642]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Sepedo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
n. The 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5ECA0D65950DF9F4" box="[462,588,1617,1643]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5ECA0D65969CF9F4" box="[462,477,1617,1642]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5EE80D65950DF9F4" box="[492,588,1617,1642]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group as defined by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA74AE5D56AD00D5C430D65931CF9F5" author="Knutson" box="[839,1117,1617,1643]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="60" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" refString="Knutson, L. &amp; Orth, R. E. (2001) Sepedon mcphersoni, n. sp., key to North American Sepedon, groups in Sepedon s. s., and intra- and intergeneric comparison (Diptera: Sciomyzidae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 103, 620 - 635." type="journal article" year="2001">
Knutson &amp; Orth (
<number id="3DFE2533D56AD00D5B130D659315F9F5" box="[1047,1108,1617,1643]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
thus does not include only one species with a Holarctic distribution but two different species, the Nearctic 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5B950D4C9276F90F" box="[1169,1335,1656,1682]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5B950D4C93E1F90F" box="[1169,1184,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5BB50D4C9276F90F" box="[1201,1335,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Palaearctic 
<taxonomicName id="4C364C97D56AD00D5E1B0DAB96DDF926" box="[287,412,1694,1720]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E1B0DAB966CF926" box="[287,301,1695,1720]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B942EB06D56AD00D5E380DAB96DDF926" box="[316,412,1695,1720]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
